Better than I'd have expected, all things considered.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Approval greater than 10 for the player.

Text.Value: My kin's heirlooms should not be in your hands.
I said keep out of it. In fact, forget it entirely.

Admit it - there's a cure for ceremorphosis in that thing, isn't there?

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Intended as a joke - not a serious accusation

Text.Value: You can really appreciate the darkness out here in the wilds. Not like in the city, where they keep lamps burning all hours. It's not natural.

EditorData.NodeContext: A little philosophical (also keen to nudge conversation away from the gith artefact)

Text.Value: *The box is inscribed with glyphs similar to those used by the githyanki.*

That's not for you to decide. There's a world beyond us. I'd like to be alone now, please.

EditorData.stateContext: Shadowheart standing  facing the player, box NOT in hand

Text.Value: Don't be so cynical. It won't help us.
Leave.
To you, perhaps. For me, it's perfect. I think I'll enjoy it by myself for a while, if you don't mind.

EditorData.NodeContext: Politely getting rid of the player.

Text.Value: I felt that - are you really surprised I won't open up when you try to fumble in my head? Leave me alone.

Text.Value: *The runes engraved on the black metal mean nothing to you. You keep examining it.*
A poor answer. I expected more openness from you.
Not much of an answer. I'd hoped for more openness.
My, quite charming when you want to be, aren't you? Maybe save some for the next time we have to talk our way past a sentry or the like.
Let me try - I always enjoy opening up what I'm not supposed to.
You can really appreciate the quiet here. Not like in the city, where noise and life scarcely ever falls silent. It's not natural.

Text.Value: The company's the worst part.

Text.Value: It won't. But I prefer it to just being frightened. I'd like to be alone now, please.
I'd like some time alone now. We'll talk soon.
Keep out of it.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Approval less than 0  for the player

Text.Value: Speak plainly. What are you doing with a gith artefact?
Nothing like a little calm and quiet after all we've been through.
Honestly? Miserable. I'd rather spend the night just about anywhere else but here.
Hmm. In that case, let me spare you the worst. Good night.
*Shadowheart's attention is consumed by a strange box that she turns over in her hands.*

Text.Value: To some, perhaps. But I'll enjoy the dark while I can. Alone, if you don't mind.

No harm in brightening up the gloom. It's comforting, safe.
Leave.
A bold statement, if not an accurate one. Leave me be.
I wish that was true. But I've seen plenty of blood spilled for just those kinds of things. The world will keep on scheming, no matter what happens to us.
*You feel Shadowheart's deep protectiveness of the artefact. Though she doesn't understand it, she believes that her fate is entwined with it somehow.*
*Shadowheart's attention is consumed by a strange box that she turns over in her hands.*

*It bears engravings resembling githyanki scripture.*

Text.Value: Use the parasite - see what she's hiding.

*You tuck it away again. Your duty is to deliver it - not understand it.*

Leave.
Keep focused. Whatever that thing is, it's not important.
I can't promise that'll be any time soon, but thank you, all the same.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: ~Shadowheart turns the puzzle box over in her hands, looking for a way to open it while seated on the ground

Synopsis: Shadowheart examines the mysterious puzzle box that she's been closely guarding. She has a mission to deliver this item to her cloister in Baldur's Gate, though doesn't truly know what it is. She tries to understand it, and possibly draws the attention of one of her companions - she shuts them down when they ask her about it, however. Note: a version this scene may have already occurred in the Druid Grove - this is a fallback that occurs at the party's campsite.
